In French slang, the word "gahouler" (or "cahouler") expresses the idea of "whispering". But as the word passed into the Creole language it transformed slightly to "gaoulé", and took on a sense of mischievous public behavior, or "dirty dancing" -- i.e., sensual, licentious dancing as opposed to the stylized dancing popular in Europe. The term came to be used to name a slave revolt on the island of Martinique in 1717 due to a remark, in an official report of that uprising, that a slave was alleged to have observed in amazement that "White people are just as good at 'gaoulé' as blacks are!"